            <h2>Writing for Web Applications</h2>

            <p>Eyetracking research shows that people scan text in various patterns; The most common being the "F" pattern<sup>[1]</sup>. Forming a literal "F" shape, this pattern can also be synonymous with "fast."  That's how users prefer to read content. </p>

            <p><b>Besides the first few sentences, it is unlikely for a user to read a paragraph of text with their full attention</b>. These chances only diminish as they scroll further down the page.</p> 

            <p>This is why text must be concise in a web application. Anything longer than two sentences will likely cause the user's attention to stray. </p>

            <hr />

            <p class="small text-muted">[1: <a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/f-shaped-pattern-reading-web-content/" target="_blank">nngroup.com</a>] Users first read in a <b>horizontal movement</b>, usually across the upper part of the content area. This initial element forms the F's top bar. Next, users move a little ways down the page and read a few words across in a <b>second horizontal movement</b>. This action forms the F's lower bar.  Finally, users perform a brisk scan down the content's left side in a <b>vertical movement</b>. This action forms the F's stem.</p>

            <hr />

            <p>The typical page in an application focuses on either collecting or reporting information. People do not sign in to an application eager to read paragraphs of technical or instructional information. Once a user has grown accustomed to an application, they will likely never read the text again. This is why the interface should center around the information it is presenting or asking for. Text fills up the tiny places around those elements, explaining what they are and how they will respond to changes. Text should never get in the way. An application's usability can skyrocket when adhering to a few simple writing habits:</p>

            <ol>
                <li><p class="lead">Let the Design do the Talking</p>
                <p>As often as possible, "show, don't tell."  A self-explanatory interface outperforms one that is not. Rely on design patterns to explain the functionality and context of an element or page. Explanatory text should be used only in special cases.</p></li>

                <li><p class="lead">Chunk Content</p>
                <p>Chunking makes content more scannable by breaking it into manageable sections. It's much less likely for a user to feel overwhelmed when paragrahs are broken up into parts.</p></li>

                <li><p class="lead">Use Simple and Concise Sentences</p>
                <p>Start content with the most important piece of information so readers can get the main point, regardless of how much they read. The ideal standard is no more than 20 words per sentence, five sentences per paragraph. Use dashes instead of semi-colons, or break the sentence into two.</p></li>

                <li><p class="lead">Maintain a Reasonable Reading Level</p>
                <p>Beyond avoiding complex sentences, complex words or phrases can impede a user's workflow. Consider the possibility of a user knowing english as a second language. Or if they lack a high-school education. Maintaining a lower reading level provides access to a larger audience of users and often results in a higher quality of writing.</p></li>

                <li><p class="lead">Use Active Voice</p>
                <p>In a sentence written in the active voice, the subject of the sentence performs the action. In a sentence written in the passive voice the subject receives the action. Passive voice sentences often use more words, can be vague, and can lead to a tangle of prepositional phrases. Active voice ensure credit is given for every action, providing enough information to explain a problem and how to fix it.</p></li>

                <li><p class="lead">Avoid Using Adverbs</p>
                <p>Like dandelions, the use of one adverb can often multiply into many. Adverbs are used to modify a verb, often end in "-ly", and can quickly clutter a piece of writing when left unchecked. Instead of "very hot," consider only saying "hot," or using a more percise word like "scorching."</p></li>
                
            </ol>

